yeah, the library/museum is the creator of the photo! whether the photo itself can actually be considered copyright is, as some people have said here, a bit dubious. but museums often get around this by only putting a low res photo online, so you have to go through them for the printable version
i worked in an archives doing digitisation once! it was crazy time consuming, those big ol scanners are not fast! plus most archives are at least a little haunted. hope you love the book btw :)
yes, getty release high res scans of all of their manuscripts for free! love those guys!
it's unfortunate, i do understand it because digitising is very expensive and time consuming for museums and libraries which are already underfunded, but still think public domain is best!

yea, the page itself isn't copyrighted! whether a faithful reproduction of a 2d object can be treated as a photo varies by country, eg in the us it was ruled that it cant be but some organizations just release super low res images to the public so you have to pay their fees lol

around 220 of the 250ish images were released by their libraries/museums under a public domain or similar license, meaning they can be used for free. the remaining 30ish had to be licensed and paid for, which was quite a complex and pricy process!
